{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501724"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:32:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:32:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1782"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1782"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.03,0.1,0.78,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1782"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44484"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1782"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1782"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29366"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"279"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20"},{"type":"contributions","id":"107"},{"type":"contributions","id":"166"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44484"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with intermittent tingling of her left hand for two to three weeks, which becomes worse after exercising. Six months ago, she experienced two days of intermittent flashes in the left eye with associated visual blurring and retro-orbital pain. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She smokes five cigarettes a day. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn neurological examination weakness in the right upper limb, most notably wrist and finger flexion and finger abduction, as well as reduced pain and temperature sensation of her left hand is noted. Her visual acuity is 6/6 (right), 6/9-1 (left). Fundoscopic examination is normal. Her extra-ocular movements are smooth, with a full range and no diplopia or nystagmus. All other neurological findings are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Motor neurone disease","Migraine with aura","Myasthenia gravis","Multiple sclerosis","Ischaemic Stroke"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of disseminated neurology in space and time, particularly with suspicion of an episode of optic neuritis six months ago, suggests an autoimmune demyelinating disorder, such as \u003Cstrong\u003Emultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E. This is supported by the presence of Uhthoff\u0027s phenomenon, in which exercising (and thus elevating core body temperature) resulted in worsening of her symptoms. Cigarette smoking has also been associated with the pathogenesis of multiple sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe episodic nature of this presentation, in addition to the history of visual distortion, detracts from a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Emotor neurone disease.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigraine with aura \u003C/strong\u003Eis unlikely, given that she does not report a history of headaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransient ischaemic attack (TIA) \u003C/strong\u003Eis unlikely, given her age, and the fact that her deficits are bilateral i.e. right-sided paresis and left-sided paraesthesia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyasthenia gravis\u003C/strong\u003E may present in two forms: ocular or generalised, with muscle weakness and muscle fatigability without sensory deficits. There is no extra-ocular muscle weakness noted on examination, and her muscle weakness is localised to the right hand.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intermittent visual disturbances, together with motor and sensory changes suggests an underlying autoimmune demyelinating disorder."],"references":["Yamout BI, Alroughani R. Multiple Sclerosis Semin Neurol 2018; 38:212-25."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29366"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1782"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29366"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-19T17:47:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-19T17:47:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1782"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44484"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"da